{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"842bef72-e0aa-4fa4-b9bb-f7ee3f29f450","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues after updating, you can also try `dotnet workload install maui` to ensure the MAUI workload is explicitly installed for your new SDK band.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"35cb4674-d610-41ab-a353-cf41216046c0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":245,"requestId":"1433:2A9B4:6EBB8A0:76FBAEA:6A03CBF8"},"id":"52ec3665-e3d2-4a61-a66d-15a4d0b162e6","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:55:28.567Z","parentId":"3e7f986c-e8ae-4e06-8c9f-3c8392337e43"}
